<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-04-09T23:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-04-09T23:36:00-05:00" n="1036" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1036">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.113/364.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-09T22:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">April 9, 1912—10 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The shipment of arms for the American colony will leave Vera Cruz
                            to-night. Owing to the duties—about $7,500 gold, and the Chargé for the
                            special train and escort, about $750 gold—the price of each rifle, with
                            100 rounds of ammunition, will amount to about $20 gold.</p>
                        <p>No guns or ammunition will be delivered by the military attaché except
                            upon payment either by the committee or by individuals.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>